   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Gaussian process regression with varying output noise"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8bf6997a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This notebook shows how to construct a Gaussian process model where different noise is assumed for different data points. The model is:\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{align}\n",
    "f(\\cdot) &\\sim \\mathcal{GP}\\big(0, k(\\cdot, \\cdot)\\big) \\\\\n",
    "y_i | f, x_i &\\sim \\mathcal N\\big(y_i; f(x_i), \\sigma^2_i\\big)\n",
    "\\end{align}\n",
    "\n",
    "We'll demonstrate three methods for specifying the data-point specific noise:\n",
    "* First we'll show how to fit the noise variance to a simple function.\n",
    "* In the second demonstration we'll assume that the data comes from two different groups and show how to learn separate noise variance for the groups.\n",
    "* Third we'll assume you have multiple samples at each location $x$ and show how to use the empirical variance."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "71b1d6dd",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-08T13:03:20.624848Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-08T13:03:20.623948Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-08T13:03:20.635676Z",

    "optimizer_config = dict(maxiter=reduce_in_tests(1000))\n",

   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "To help us later we'll first define a small function for plotting data with predictions:"

   "metadata": {
    "execution": {

     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-08T13:03:27.532469Z",

   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def plot_distribution(\n",
    "    X: gf.base.AnyNDArray,\n",
    "    Y: gf.base.AnyNDArray,\n",
    "    X_plot: Optional[gf.base.AnyNDArray] = None,\n",
    "    mean_plot: Optional[gf.base.AnyNDArray] = None,\n",
    "    var_plot: Optional[gf.base.AnyNDArray] = None,\n",
    "    X_err: Optional[gf.base.AnyNDArray] = None,\n",
    "    mean_err: Optional[gf.base.AnyNDArray] = None,\n",
    "    var_err: Optional[gf.base.AnyNDArray] = None,\n",
    ") -> None:\n",
    "    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))\n",
    "\n",
    "    X = X.squeeze(axis=-1)\n",
    "    Y = Y.squeeze(axis=-1)\n",
    "    plt.scatter(X, Y, color=\"gray\", alpha=0.8)\n",
    "\n",
    "    def get_confidence_bounds(\n",
    "        mean: gf.base.AnyNDArray, var: gf.base.AnyNDArray\n",
    "    ) -> Tuple[gf.base.AnyNDArray, gf.base.AnyNDArray]:\n",
    "        std = np.sqrt(var)\n",
    "        return mean - 1.96 * std, mean + 1.96 * std\n",
    "\n",
    "    if X_plot is not None:\n",
    "        assert mean_plot is not None\n",
    "        assert var_plot is not None\n",
    "        X_plot = X_plot.squeeze(axis=-1)\n",
    "        mean_plot = mean_plot.squeeze(axis=-1)\n",
    "        var_plot = var_plot.squeeze(axis=-1)\n",
    "        lower_plot, upper_plot = get_confidence_bounds(mean_plot, var_plot)\n",
    "        plt.fill_between(X_plot, lower_plot, upper_plot, color=\"silver\", alpha=0.25)\n",
    "        plt.plot(X_plot, lower_plot, color=\"silver\")\n",
    "        plt.plot(X_plot, upper_plot, color=\"silver\")\n",
    "        plt.plot(X_plot, mean_plot, color=\"black\")\n",
    "\n",
    "    if X_err is not None:\n",
    "        assert mean_err is not None\n",
    "        assert var_err is not None\n",
    "        lower_err, upper_err = get_confidence_bounds(mean_err, var_err)\n",
    "        plt.vlines(X_err, lower_err, upper_err, color=\"black\")\n",
    "\n",
    "    plt.xlim([0, 1])\n",
    "    plt.show()"
   ]
  },

    "## Demo 1: known noise variances\n",
    "### Generate data\n",
    "We create a utility function to generate synthetic data, including noise that varies amongst the data:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "036ee759",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-08T13:03:27.543432Z",

     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-08T13:03:27.547537Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-08T13:03:27.546862Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def generate_data() -> Tuple[gf.base.AnyNDArray, gf.base.AnyNDArray]:\n",
    "    rng = np.random.default_rng(42)  # for reproducibility\n",
    "    X = rng.uniform(0.0, 1.0, (n_data, 1))\n",
    "    signal = (X - 0.5) ** 2 + 0.05\n",
    "    noise_scale = 0.5 * signal\n",
    "    noise = noise_scale * rng.standard_normal((n_data, 1))\n",
    "    Y = signal + noise\n",
    "    return X, Y\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "X, Y = generate_data()"
   ]
  },

    "## Demo 2: grouped noise variances\n",
    "\n",
    "In this demo, we won't assume that the noise variances is a function of $x$, but we will assume that they're known to be in two groups. This example represents a case where we might know that data has been collected by two instruments with different fidelity, but we do not know what those fidelities are.\n",
    "\n",
    "Of course it would be straightforward to add more groups. We'll stick with two for simplicity."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "9d3a3427",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Generate data"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "id": "b82b7141",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-08T13:03:34.769744Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-08T13:03:34.769441Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-08T13:03:34.774805Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-08T13:03:34.774225Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def get_group(X: gf.base.AnyNDArray) -> gf.base.AnyNDArray:\n",
    "    return np.where((((0.2 < X) & (X < 0.4)) | ((0.7 < X) & (X < 0.8))), 0, 1)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def generate_grouped_data() -> Tuple[gf.base.AnyNDArray, gf.base.AnyNDArray]:\n",
    "    rng = np.random.default_rng(42)  # for reproducibility\n",
    "    X = rng.uniform(0.0, 1.0, (n_data, 1))\n",
    "    signal = np.sin(6 * X)\n",
    "    noise_scale = 0.1 + 0.4 * get_group(X)\n",
    "    noise = noise_scale * rng.standard_normal((n_data, 1))\n",
    "    Y = signal + noise\n",
    "    return X, Y\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "X, Y = generate_grouped_data()"
   ]
  },

    "### Data structure\n",
    "\n",
    "To model the different noise groups, we need to let the model know which group each data point belongs to. We'll do that by appending a column with the group to the $x$ data:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "id": "8b73f997",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-08T13:03:36.381521Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-08T13:03:36.381239Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-08T13:03:36.384622Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-08T13:03:36.384111Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "X_and_group = np.hstack([X, get_group(X)])\n",
    "X_plot_and_group = np.hstack([X_plot, get_group(X_plot)])"

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4dbe6723",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Use multiple functions for the noise variance\n",
    "\n",
    "To model this we will create two noise variance functions, each of which are just a constant, and then switch between them depending on the group labels.\n",
    "\n",
    "Notice that we initialize the constant functions to a positive value. They would have defaulted to `0.0`, but that wouldn't work for a variance, which must be strictly positive."
   ]
  },

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4086fe8b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Demo 3: Empirical noise variance\n",
    "\n",
    "In this demo we will assume that you have multiple measurements at each $x$ location, and want to use the empirical variance at each location."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c61f904f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Generate data"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,
   "id": "3f4ae844",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-08T13:03:39.378912Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-08T13:03:39.378604Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-08T13:03:39.383857Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-08T13:03:39.383345Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "n_data = reduce_in_tests(20)\n",
    "n_repeats = reduce_in_tests(10)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def generate_empiricial_noise_data() -> Tuple[gf.base.AnyNDArray, gf.base.AnyNDArray]:\n",
    "    rng = np.random.default_rng(42)  # for reproducibility\n",
    "    X = rng.uniform(0.0, 1.0, (n_data, 1))\n",
    "    signal = np.sin(6 * X)\n",
    "    noise_scale = rng.uniform(0.1, 1.0, (n_data, 1))\n",
    "    noise = noise_scale * rng.standard_normal((n_data, n_repeats))\n",
    "    Y = signal + noise\n",
    "    return X, Y\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "X, Y = generate_empiricial_noise_data()\n",
    "Y_mean = np.mean(Y, axis=-1, keepdims=True)\n",
    "Y_var = np.var(Y, axis=-1, keepdims=True)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "7a1f260d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "For the sake of plotting we'll create flat lists of (x, y) pairs:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 18,
   "id": "acb36704",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-08T13:03:39.386273Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-08T13:03:39.386022Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-08T13:03:39.554857Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-08T13:03:39.554184Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1500x500 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "X_flat = np.broadcast_to(X, Y.shape).reshape((-1, 1))\n",
    "Y_flat = Y.reshape((-1, 1))\n",
    "plot_distribution(X_flat, Y_flat)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "9bdb2dd5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Data structure\n",
    "\n",
    "Our GPs don't like it when multiple data points occupy the same $x$ location. So we'll reduce this dataset to the means and the variances at each $x$, and use a custom function to model inject the empirical variances into the model."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 19,
   "id": "00ca9316",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-08T13:03:39.557717Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-08T13:03:39.557421Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-08T13:03:39.560594Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-08T13:03:39.560077Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "Y_mean = np.mean(Y, axis=-1, keepdims=True)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "23bba4cc",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Fit a naive model\n",
    "\n",
    "Again we'll start by fitting a naive GPR, to demonstrate the problem.\n",
    "\n",
    "Notice that this case is somewhat different from what we did above. Here we are not modelling $Y$, but the mean of $Y$, so the noise variance is not our uncertainty of $Y$, but our uncertainty of the mean of $Y$. Furthermore, while the naive model assumes a constant noise variance, the custom noise variance function we will develop below will only model the noise variance at the points where we have data, thus we cannot plot a continuous uncertainty. Instead, the shaded gray area is the confidence interval of $f$, and we use vertical black lines to indicate the confidence interval of the $Y$ mean."
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "### Create custom function for the noise variance\n",
    "\n",
    "We're modelling the `Y_mean` and its standard error is `Y_var / n_repeats`. We will create a simple function that ignores its input and returns these values as a constant. This will obviously only work for the `X` that corresponds to the `Y` we computed the variance of - that is good enough for model training, but notice that it will not allow us to use `predict_y`."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 22,
   "id": "92b1aa03",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-08T13:03:40.271882Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-08T13:03:40.271601Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-08T13:03:40.275635Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-08T13:03:40.275111Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "class FixedVarianceOfMean(gf.functions.Function):\n",
    "    def __init__(self, Y: gf.base.AnyNDArray):\n",
    "        n_repeats = Y.shape[-1]\n",
    "        self.var_mean = np.var(Y, axis=-1, keepdims=True) / n_repeats\n",
    "\n",
    "    @inherit_check_shapes\n",
    "    def __call__(self, X: gf.base.TensorType) -> tf.Tensor:\n",
    "        return self.var_mean"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "de7497d9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now we can plug that into our model:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",

       "</thead>\n",
       "<tbody>\n",
       "<tr><td>GPR.kernel.variance    </td><td>Parameter</td><td>Softplus   </td><td>       </td><td>True       </td><td>()     </td><td>float64</td><td style=\"text-align: right;\">0.60614</td></tr>\n",
       "<tr><td>GPR.kernel.lengthscales</td><td>Parameter</td><td>Softplus   </td><td>       </td><td>True       </td><td>()     </td><td>float64</td><td style=\"text-align: right;\">0.26903</td></tr>\n",
